@node Intro


 1. Introduction :

  Purpose      : It lists, adds TAGs, edits TAGs, converts, cleans, gives
                 the duration of your MP3 (MPEG Audio) files.
               
                 watch the @{" examples :) " link Examples}

  Release date : 17.09.99

  Author       : @{" HEINRICH Patrick " link Author}

  Distribution : It's free :) (you can't ask money for it)
                 C source available (ask it :)

  Disclaimer   : I DO NOT TAKE ANY RESPONSIBILITY FOR ANYTHING THAT COULD
                 BE CAUSED BY THIS PROGRAM !
                 IT IS NOT LEGAL TO HAVE MP3 FILES FROM SONGS YOU HAVEN'T
                 BOUGHT ON CDS !


                                     @{" Back " link Main}  


@endnode
@node History


 2. H!story :

  V0.01 : [07/08/97]
          - the 't' option worked ;)
       
  V0.02 : [08/09/97]
          - added the comment 'c' option
          - some code cleanup

  V0.03 : [28/10/97] 
          - added total size (in bytes and megabytes)
          - can use multiple files or dirs or volumes
            (you can mix dirs, files, volumes ...)
          
          ex:  MPTool t Mpeg1: Mpeg2: Mpeg3:  now works fine ...
          or   MPTool t Sd0:1.mp3 Sd0:2.mp3 Sd0:Dance/        

  V0.04 : [02/04/98]
          - added the 'w' option to cut the wave header of a MPEG file
          - added the 'a' option to automatically convert while listing
   
  V1.00 : [06/05/98]
          - rewrite most of the program (take a look at the C source)
          - the way of using it has radically changed
          - now MPTool has 12 options that can be used together !!
          - handles every wave/MP3 (I hope so :)
          - handles MP3 TAGs (B,N,T options)
          - can scan files for finding MP3 in those files ! (F option)
          - can separate headers from files (F option)
          - seems good enough to be 1.00

  V1.10 : [31/08/98]  MAJOR UPDATE

          *NEW OPTIONS*
          - 3 ways of sorting a list : * by the path/file name
                                       * by the TAG's songname
                                       * by the TAG's author
          - the Album TAG Mode : it allows you to TAG all MP3s of one album 
            without having to reenter the author, album title ...
          - it can rename a file automatically using the songname of the TAG
          - it only displays the used fields of a TAG (that's to say, if the
            TAG has no comment, it won't prompt "Comment :"
          - it has a Multiple Volume Mode (that's to say, you can list several
            CDs, Zips or whatever you have :)
          - it can print dots instead of white spaces (...... 03:18)

          *IMPROVEMENTS*    
          - the way of editing TAGs is really better
          - it can wisely truncate path+name to fit 66 characters (by printing
            a [...] in the middle of the line, so you have the complete name
            of the file)
          - the Force Mode can replace a file 
            (you can use MPTool -F dh1:strangefile.mp3)
          - the Genres List can be sorted by name (g) or number (G)
          - the Genres List has been updated (145 genres)
          - the file MPTool.genres can be moved in the current directory

          *BUG FIXES* 
          - no more stack problem
          - it can use a genre number > 127
          - it should be a little bit faster   

  V1.11 : [10/09/98]  minor update

          *IMPROVEMENTS*    
          - it should detect more MPEG files

          *BUG FIXES* 
          - the total duration is displayed when using the comment option (C)
 
  V1.12 : [11/09/98]  stupid update ;)

          *BUG FIXES* 
          - while editing the 1.11, I added a stupid bug ... sorry
            the TAG reader is now fine, like in the 1.10 :)

  V1.20 : [29/10/98] [MAJOR HALLOWEEN UPDATE]

          *NEW OPTIONS*
          - the format list option (U) : you can create your own list format !
          - it can rename a MPEG file automatically using the artist AND the 
            songname in the TAG (t)

          *IMPROVEMENTS*  
          - new design
          - support of the unofficial TAG field : songnumber (Hi Tomek! :)
          - should support ALL MPEG files (MPEG1/2 Layer I/II/III)
            (thanks to a doc I found)
          - handles more infos (frequence, layer, mode ...)

          *BUG FIXES* 
          - if you enter nothing, the current working directory will be used

          Note : option 'f' has been removed (useless :)

  V1.21 : [22/12/98] [minor X-Mas'98 update]

          *BUG FIXES* 
          - removed a bug that could crash MPTool if too many files were listed

  V1.22 : [12/04/99]  minor update

          *IMPROVEMENTS*    
          - handles a "new" MP3 header (coming from the PC world ...)
          - can remove this ID3 header to clean the file (option : -F)
          
  V1.23 : [12/09/99]  minor update

          *IMPROVEMENTS*    
          - can handle "new" MP3 headers
          - cleans the file if it isn't a MPEG file (option -F)
          - forces the cleaning of a file, even if i is a MPEG (-E)

          


                                    @{" Back " link Main}  


@endnode
@node Install


 3. Installing MPTool :

 It's quite easy :

    * copy the file MPTool.Genres in c:
    * copy the file MPTool wherever you want (I suggest in c: ;)

 That's all !

 NB: MPTool uses mathieeedoubbas.library which is provided by Commodore.


                                    @{" Back " link Main}  


@endnode
@node Options


 4. MPTool's Options :

CLI>c:MPTool -h

 MPTool V1.23 '99 by HEINRICH Patrick 

 Registered to : Everybody 

 Usage : MPTool [-options] ["format string"] [file(s)/drawer(s)/device(s)]

 where options is ONE or MORE of the 24 following options :

  @{" a "link Optionsa}: produces a TAG list sorted by 'artist'
  @{" A "link OptionsA1}: Album TAG Mode activated
  @{" B "link OptionsB}: reads a TAG (if there's one)
  @{" C "link OptionsC}: adds duration and kbps in comment (deletes old comments)
  @{" d "link Optionsd}: prints dots (.) instead of white spaces
  @{" D "link OptionsD1}: Deep Scan Mode activated
  @{" E "link OptionsE}: forces the cleaning
  @{" F "link OptionsF1}: forces the removal of a header ; see the doc
  @{" H "link OptionsH}: removes wave headers
  @{" L "link OptionsL}: lists the files
  @{" m "link Optionsm}: Multiple Volume Mode in a silent way
  @{" M "link OptionsM1}: Multiple Volume Mode activated
  @{" n "link Optionsn}: produces a TAG list sorted by 'songname'
  @{" N "link OptionsN1}: removes TAG from files
  @{" Q "link OptionsQ}: Quicksort Mode
  @{" r "link Optionsr}: renames files using TAG's songname (if there's one)
  @{" R "link OptionsR1}: Recursive Mode activated (scans all subdrawers)
  @{" s "link Optionss}: forces empty TAG fields to appear
  @{" S "link OptionsS1}: adds symbols while listing (@:deep scan file,#:wave header)
  @{" t "link OptionsT1}: renames files using TAG's artist and songname
  @{" T "link OptionsT}: adds a TAG to a MP3 file or modifies an existing one
  @{" U "link OptionsU}: uses YOUR own listing format
  @{" z "link Optionsz}: no initial colored MPTool title
  @{" Z "link OptionsZ1}: no final sum up


 You can mix the options and the order has no effect : -dBRQ = -QRdB = ...

 Warning : Options are CASE SENSITIVE !!!

 You can use MPTool as a button in DirectoryOpus or with ClassAction :

 I use in DOpus  AMIGADOS   c:MPTool -RL {F}
                 [x] do all files
                 [x] output to window
                 [x] run asynchronously
                 [x] window close button
 and called this button MPEGSIZE.
 You can create lots of other buttons ... (TAGMP3, NOTAG ...)

 Hav' fun !



                                      @{" Back " link Main}

@endnode
@node Optionsa


## a ##


It scans the given drawers and selects TAGged MP3 files, sorts them by artist
and displays the list ( -aR for working on subdrawers)

Example :

CLI>MPTool -a "aq2:Electronic Music/Euro Techno/"


