@endnode
@node OptionsA1


## A ##  :  The Album TAG Mode


It was created to allow you to TAG an album in a very short laps of time :

* you are asked for the artist, album title, the year of edition, a comment
  and a genre
* those data will be used as default to TAG all files you asked to TAG
  ( but you still can modify each field :)


                            @{" Back To The Options " link Options}  


@endnode
@node OptionsB


## B ##


It reads (and displays) a TAG from a file if there is a TAG !


                            @{" Back To The Options " link Options}  


@endnode
@node OptionsC


## C ##


It puts the duration, the kbps, the MPEG version and the layer as a comment
of your file.

  !!!  Warning : the old comment will be trashed.  !!!


                            @{" Back To The Options " link Options}  


@endnode
@node Optionsd


## d ##


It prints dots (...) instead of white spaces. I think it makes it easier to 
read.
This option only works with the QuickSort (Q) option selected.


                            @{" Back To The Options " link Options}  


@endnode
@node OptionsD1
  

## D ##  :  The Deep Scan Mode


It activates the deep scan mode : indeed, some files have a text file added 
in the beginning; therefore MPTool checks the first 8 Kb for a MP3 header (it
is slower... but can find more files).

  !!! Warning : can select wrong files since some files could contain a MP3
                header without being MP3 files


                            @{" Back To The Options " link Options}  


@endnode
@node OptionsE


## E ##  :  Force the cleaning


Same option than @{" F " link OptionsF1} without the header check ...



                            @{" Back To The Options " link Options}  


@endnode
@node OptionsF1


## F ##


New since 1.23 : if the file has already a MPEG header, it won't be cleaned.
If you want to force the cleaning, use option -E

This option has a special use : 

     It can only be used alone.
     It forces the removal of a pseudo header : if you have a MP3 file and 
     the header is not standard, use this option

     !! Warning : Special Syntax !!

                MPTool -F <infile>
             or MPTool -F <infile> <outfile>
             or MPTool -F <infile> <outfile> <outfileheader>
                (if you want read the header before trashing it)

So you can "clean" your header to use them with Songplayer.
 
Amazing what you can find in MP3 header :

example : the header of desire.mp3 (saved by MPTool in a text file)


  
