                            @{" Back To The Options " link Options}  


@endnode
@node OptionsS1


## S ##  :  Symbols


When L is selected, if the file is a wave file : a '#' before the name
if the file has been found thanks to deep scan : a '@' before the name


                            @{" Back To The Options " link Options}  


@endnode
@node OptionsT1


## t ##  :  Rename a MPEG File using the artist name and the songname


It takes the artist - songname of a TAGged file to rename it :)
Useful if you have badly named files with TAGs.

Warning : only the first 30 characters will be used :) since AmigaDOS
          supports 30 characters filename !


                            @{" Back To The Options " link Options}  

@endnode
@node OptionsT


##áT ##  :  TAG a file


It adds a TAG to a MP3 file or modifies an existing one.
You have only to fill the fields.

You are limited to 30 characters for texts and 4 for the year.

The Song Number is limited to 31.

While editing a new TAG, enter nothing will suppose you don't want to use
the songnumber field.

While editing an existing TAG, entering 0 will suppress the field
(so you can use a 30 char comment :)

If the file has already a TAG, this TAG will appear and you can still
change it.

      g : name sorted genres list
      G : number sorted genres list
      r : restart the TAGging of the file
      q : exiting without writing the TAG


                            @{" Back To The Options " link Options}  


@endnode
@node OptionsU


##áU ##  :  use your own list format

It allows you to create your own list format : you give MPTool the way you
want him to format your list.
This is done by entering a string after the options :

MPTool -Options "Format String" ...

example of a format string : "%30N %20TA %V-%L   %10S"

In the string you specify what you want by typing the following instructions :
[ Some fields have a pre-defined width, others have to be defined ([n] = an 
integer) by the user ]

%[width][name of the field]

Available fields :
----------------

%[n]N  : name of the file    ( ex: %30N if you want a 30 chars width)
%[n]P  : path + name of the file
%V     : MPEG Version     [5 chars]
%M     : MPEG Mode        [8 chars]
%L     : Layer            [3 chars]
%K     : Bitrate          [3 chars]
%[n]F  : sampling frequence  (I suggest %2F for the kHz or %5F for Hz)
%m     : minutes          [2 chars]
%z     : seconds          [2 chars]
%[n]S  : size of the file (in bytes)

TAg fields : (slower since MPTool has to read the TAG)

%[n]TN : TAG's songname
%[n]Tn : TAG's songname or filename if the file has no TAG
%[n]TA : TAG's artist
%[n]TL : TAG's album
%TY    : TAG's year       [4 chars]
%[n]TC : TAG's comment
%[n]TG : TAG's genre
%TS    : TAG's songnumber [2 chars]


                           watch the @{" examples :) " link Examples}


                            @{" Back To The Options " link Options}  


@endnode
@node Optionsz


## z ##


It prevents MPTool from displaying a colored MPTool title.


                            @{" Back To The Options " link Options}  


@endnode
@node OptionsZ1


## Z ##


It prevents MPTool from making a summary of what it has found.


                            @{" Back To The Options " link Options}  


@endnode
@node Examples


 5. Examples :


  5 examples to show you what MPTool can do :

       c:MPTool

       @{" 1. " link ex1}
        |
         \_  -zQ "aq2:Electronic Music/" 

       @{" 2. " link ex2}
        |
         \_  -zQU "| %30Tn | %20TA | %5FHz | %TY |" "aq2:Electronic Music/"

       @{" 3. " link ex3}  
        |
         \_  -QU "| %TS | %30TN | %10TG | %m:%z |" "aq2:Dance/" "LisaLand:Louise - Woman In Me/"

       @{" 4. " link ex4}
        |
         \_  -RQU "| %60P | %m:%z | %Kkbps |" aq2:

       @{" 5. " link ex5}
        |
         \_  -RBQU "%66P %m:%z %Kkbps" aq2:MyMP3/


                                      @{" Back " link Main}




@endnode
